The Nigerian Bar Association (NBA), Ado Ekiti branch has stressed the need to conduct compulsory psychiatric test on the would be operatives of Ekiti State Security Network Agency called ‘Amotekun’ to make its operations efficient. The body said the step became necessary in view of alleged incessant misconduct of conventional security agents ,leading to brutality and unwarranted incarceration and killings of Nigerians . The State House of Assembly had last Friday passed the bill establishing the security into law and awaiting the Governor Kayode Fayemi assent for its full takeoff. The NBA Chairman, Ado Ekiti Branch, Barrister Olakanmi Falade ,  who spoke on Sunday said he had earlier made the suggestion at the Assembly’s public hearing on the outfit as part of the prerequisites for qualification for Amotekun operatives to inject sanity into their conduct and operations. Falade pointed out that section 19 of the Ekiti State Security Network Agency bill sent to the House spoke about qualification, but issue of mental stability was not put into account, which he said spurred him to raise observation about that. “Under the interpretation of sections, arms should not mean firearms alone, it should also include axes, cutlasses, even stick. That I think would have been taken to into account before passage. “Also,  I proposed that in addition to criteria for employment  of officials, a mandatory psychiatric test should be added in the law as stated in Section 19 which dealt with recruitment.” “The passed bill before transmission to the executive with amendments should include this. The mental stability of whoever carries arms matter to Nigerians. “We have seen cases of how Nigerians were being abused by security operatives. We have seen how those that were supposed to guarantee safety ended up killing innocent people over flimsy excuses. “I appeal to the House to effect this while doing the amendment before transmitting to the executive.’’